Ruabon, Wrexham, Wales, Verenigd Koninkrijk","of,,Denbighshire,Wales":"Denbighshire, Wales, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Wales":"Wales, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"about 1295–after 1332":"about 1295–after 1332","1295–1332":"1295–1332","1300–Male":"1300–Deceased","–Male":"Deceased","1300–Female":"1300–Deceased","1325–1358":"1325–1358","1325–Male":"1325–Deceased","1270–Male":"1270–Deceased","–Female":"Deceased","1325":"1325","1358":"1358","1300":"1300","1332":"1332","1295":"1295","after 1332":"after 1332","1270":"1270","about 1295":"about 1295","ABT    1325":"about 1325","Ruabon, Wrexham, Wales, United Kingdom":"Ruabon, Wrexham, Wales, United Kingdom","of,,Denbighshire,Wales":"Denbighshire, Wales, United Kingdom","Wales":"Wales, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Iorwerth","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Traditional: from <i>iōr</i>‘ ‘lord’ + a mutated form of <i>berth</i> ‘handsome’; borne in the <i>Mabinogi</i> by the jealous brother of  Madawg , son of  Maredudd . <i>Iorwerth</i> came to be regarded as a Welsh equivalent of  Edward , but it has no actual connection with that name."],"variants":[{"name":"Yorath","meanings":["Anglicized form of   Iorwerth   or, in some cases, a transferred use of the surname derived from it."]}]},{"name":"\"Fychan\"","type":"FIRST","meanings":["Welsh: A Welsh name of great antiquity, from vyckan, little, small; i.e. small in stature. Compare the surname Bychan and the Armoric Le Bihan."],"variants":[]},{"name":"ap","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of any of the names beginning with this syllable."],"variants":[{"name":"Alexander","meanings":["From the Latin form of the Greek name <i>Alexandros</i>, from <i>alexein</i> ‘to defend’ + <i>anēr</i> ‘man, warrior’ (genitive <i>andros</i>). The name became extremely popular in the post-classical period, and was borne by several individuals in the New Testament and some early Christian saints. Its use as a common given name throughout Europe, however, derives largely from the fame of  Alexander the Great , King of Macedon (  356–323  bc  ), around whom a large body of popular legend grew up in late antiquity, much of which came to be embodied in the medieval ‘Alexander romances’."]},{"name":"Alan","meanings":["Of Celtic origin and uncertain derivation (possibly a diminutive of a word meaning ‘rock’). It was introduced into England by  Breton  followers of  William the Conqueror , most notably  Alan , Earl of Brittany, who was rewarded for his services with vast estates in the newly conquered kingdom. In Britain the variants  <b>Allan</b>  and  <b>Allen</b>  are considerably less frequent, and generally represent transferred uses of surname forms, whereas in America all three forms of the name are approximately equally common.  See also  Alun ."]},{"name":"Albert","meanings":["From an Old French name, <i>Albert</i>, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>adal</i> ‘noble’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to England, displacing the Old English form <i>Æþelbeorht</i>. The name is popular in a variety of forms in Western Europe, and has been traditional in a number of European princely families. It was out of favour in England for centuries, however, and the revival of its popularity in the 19th century was largely in honour of  Queen Victoria's  consort,  Prince Albert of Saxe-Coburg-Gotha ."]}]},{"name":"Iorwerth","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Traditional: from <i>iōr</i>‘ ‘lord’ + a mutated form of <i>berth</i> ‘handsome’; borne in the <i>Mabinogi</i> by the jealous brother of  Madawg , son of  Maredudd . <i>Iorwerth</i> came to be regarded as a Welsh equivalent of  Edward , but it has no actual connection with that name."],"variants":[{"name":"Yorath","meanings":["Anglicized form of   Iorwerth   or, in some cases, a transferred use of the surname derived from it."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Iorwerth \"Fychan\" ap Iorwerth was born about 1295, in Wales, United Kingdom as the son of Iorwerth ap Awr and Margaret verch Ednyfed. He had at least 1 son and 1 daughter with Margred verch Madog. He died after 1332."},"et":{"about 1295–after 1332":"umbes 1295–pärast 1332","1295–1332":"1295–1332","1300–Male":"1300–Surnud","–Male":"Surnud","1300–Female":"1300–Surnud","1325–1358":"1325–1358","1325–Male":"1325–Surnud","1270–Male":"1270–Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","1325":"1325","1358":"1358","1300":"1300","1332":"1332","1295":"1295","after 1332":"pärast 1332","1270":"1270","about 1295":"umbes 1295","ABT    1325":"umbes 1325","Ruabon, Wrexham, Wales, United Kingdom":"Ruabon, Wrexham, Wales, United Kingdom","of,,Denbighshire,Wales":"Denbighshire, Wales, United Kingdom","Wales":"Wales, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"about 1295–after 1332":"noin 1295–1332 jälkeen","1295–1332":"1295–1332","1300–Male":"1300–Kuollut","–Male":"Kuollut","1300–Female":"1300–Kuollut","1325–1358":"1325–1358","1325–Male":"1325–Kuollut","1270–Male":"1270–Kuollut","–Female":"Kuollut","1325":"1325","1358":"1358","1300":"1300","1332":"1332","1295":"1295","after 1332":"1332 jälkeen","1270":"1270","about 1295":"noin 1295","ABT    1325":"noin 1325","Ruabon, Wrexham, Wales, United Kingdom":"Ruabon, Wrexham, Wales, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","of,,Denbighshire,Wales":"Denbighshire, Wales, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Wales":"Wales, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"about 1295–after 1332":"environ 1295–après 1332","1295–1332":"1295–1332","1300–Male":"1300–Décédé","–Male":"Décédé","1300–Female":"1300–Décédée","1325–1358":"1325–1358","1325–Male":"1325–Décédé","1270–Male":"1270–Décédé","–Female":"Décédée","1325":"1325","1358":"1358","1300":"1300","1332":"1332","1295":"1295","after 1332":"après 1332","1270":"1270","about 1295":"environ 1295","ABT    132